  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Ishraq in Islam?",
  "response": "In Islam, \"Ishraq\" (\u0625\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0642) has several related meanings and implications:\n\n1. Linguistic meaning:\n- \"Ishraq\" literally means \"brightness\" or \"radiance\" in Arabic\n- It is derived from the root word \"sharq\" which means \"east\" or \"sunrise\"\n\n2. Spiritual significance:\n- Refers to a spiritual enlightenment or illumination\n- Represents the inner light of spiritual knowledge and understanding\n- Symbolizes divine guidance and inspiration\n\n3. Prayer context:\n- Ishraq prayer is a recommended (mustahabb) prayer performed shortly after sunrise\n- It is performed about 15-20 minutes after sunrise, when the sun has risen to a certain height\n- Considered a voluntary (nafl) prayer with spiritual rewards\n\n4. Philosophical dimension:\n- In Islamic philosophical tradition, Ishraq represents a mystical approach to knowledge\n- Associated with illumination and direct spiritual perception\n- Emphasizes intuitive understanding beyond rational reasoning\n\n5. Sufi interpretation:\n- In Sufi mysticism, Ishraq symbolizes divine light and spiritual awakening\n- Represents the inner journey towards understanding divine truth\n\nOverall, Ishraq encompasses spiritual enlightenment, divine illumination, and a deeper connection with Allah.",
